{"questionId":"19695","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The following table shows the systolic blood pressures, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi></math> mmHg, and the ages, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> years, of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math> male patients at a medical clinic.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/90015eda9d008836afbdc1f5480e9fcb341ba363.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The relationship between <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi></math> can be modelled by the regression line of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi></math> on <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> with&nbsp;equation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi></math> .</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn></math>‐year‐old male patient enters the medical clinic for his appointment.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Use the regression equation from part (b) to predict this patient’s systolic blood&nbsp;pressure.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>122</mn></math>&nbsp;(mmHg)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<strong>(M1)A1</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>[2 marks]</strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"19695","referenceCode":"EXN.2.SL.TZ0.4c","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Use the regression equation from part (b) to predict this patient’s systolic blood pressure.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.4—Pearsons, s